title: Met Gala 2025 Photos: Doechii, Chappell Roan, Lana Del Rey, and More
description: See what Bad Bunny, Sabrina Carpenter, Lorde, Rosalía, and others wore to the event
author: Nina Corcoran, Walden Green

text: See what Bad Bunny, Sabrina Carpenter, Lorde, Rosalía, and others wore to the eventFollowing the 2024 event, celebrities once again descended on New York’s Metropolitan Museum of Art for the annual Met Gala. The fundraiser’s dress code this year was “Tailored for You,” encouraging guests to pursue tailoring and menswear in their outfits on the carpet.The 2025 Costume Institute Benefit celebrates the Costume Institute’s new exhibition “Superfine: Tailoring Black Style,” which “presents a cultural and historical examination of Black style over three hundred years through the concept of dandyism,” per the museum.Pharrell Williams, A$AP Rocky, Colman Domingo, and Lewis Hamilton joined Vogue’s editor-in-chief, Anna Wintour, as co-chairs for this year’s gala, with LeBron James serving as an honorary chair. html:
See what Bad Bunny, Sabrina Carpenter, Lorde, Rosalía, and others wore to the event

Following the 2024 event, celebrities once again descended on New York’s Metropolitan Museum of Art for the annual Met Gala. The fundraiser’s dress code this year was “Tailored for You,” encouraging guests to pursue tailoring and menswear in their outfits on the carpet.

The 2025 Costume Institute Benefit celebrates the Costume Institute’s new exhibition “Superfine: Tailoring Black Style,” which “presents a cultural and historical examination of Black style over three hundred years through the concept of dandyism,” per the museum.

Pharrell Williams, A$AP Rocky, Colman Domingo, and Lewis Hamilton joined Vogue’s editor-in-chief, Anna Wintour, as co-chairs for this year’s gala, with LeBron James serving as an honorary chair. Check out a gallery of photos from the event below, updated with new arrivals.

Nina Corcoran joined Pitchfork as an Associate Staff Writer in 2021 after contributing to the website since 2015. She’s written for Rolling Stone, Wired, NPR, Stereogum, and elsewhere, and was previously the music editor of alt-weekly newspaper DigBoston. She’s based in Chicago. ... Read more

Walden Green is a music writer and cultural critic who joined Pitchfork in 2024. A graduate of the University of Pennsylvania, his work has appeared in Dirt, The Fader, and Philadelphia. He lives in New York. ... Read more
